04476nam a22006495i 9781442687394DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20172009onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426873947 a10.3138/97814426873942doi  a(DE-B1597)483244  a(OCoLC)1004867507  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aHC117.M243bC73 2009eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a330.97151 aCraig, Beatrice, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBackwoods Consumers and Homespun Capitalists :bThe Rise of a Market Culture in Eastern Canada /cBeatrice Craig. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2017] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures, Maps, and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. From ‘Market’ to Markets: New Trends in Rural Economic and Social History -- t1. People on the Move: Migrations and Networks -- t2. Principal Men -- t3. A Connective Enterprise: Madawaska Lumbering -- t4. Sawmills, Gristmills, and Lumber Manufacture -- t5. General Stores: Capitalism’s Beachheads or Local Traffic Controllers? -- t6. A Tale of Two Markets: Frontier Farming -- t7. A Hierarchy of Farmers: Saint John Valley Agriculture -- t8. The Homespun Paradox: Domestic Cloth Production and the Farm Economy -- t9. Consumption and the ‘World of Goods’ -- tConclusion: Domesticating the Economy, Commercializing the Household -- tAppendix 1. Sources and Methods -- tAppendix 2. Prices Used for Estimating Production and Surplus Values -- tAppendix 3. Tables -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the late eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries, a local economy made up of settlers, loggers, and business people from Lower Canada, New Brunswick, and New England was established on the banks of the Upper St. John River in an area known as the Madawaska Territory. This newly created economy was visibly part of the Atlantic capitalist system yet different in several major ways.In Backwoods Consumers and Homespun Capitalists, Béatrice Craig examines and describes this economy from its origins in the native fur trade, the growth of exportable wheat, the selling of food to new settlers, and of ton timbre to Britain. Craig vividly portrays the role of wives who sold homespun fabric and clothing to farmers, loggers, and river drivers, helping to bolster the community. The construction of saw, grist, and carding mills, and the establishment of stores, boarding houses, and taverns are all viewed as steps in the development of what the author calls "homespun capitalists." The territory also participated in the Atlantic economy as a consumer of Canadian, British, European, west and east Indian and American goods. This case study offers a unique examination of the emergence of capitalism and of a consumer society in a small, relatively remote community in the backwoods of New Brunswick.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCapitalismzNew BrunswickxHistoryy19th century. 0aRural developmentzNew BrunswickzMadawaska (County)xHistoryy19th century. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268739440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442687394423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442687394.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK